  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Matthew 5:47",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀσπάσησθε",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", “Salute,” a very slight display of love from our Western point of view, a mere civility; more significant in the East; symbolic here of friendly relations, hence Tholuck, Bleek and others interpret, “to act in a friendly manner,” which, as Meyer remarks, is, if not the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "significatio",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", at least the ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "adsignificatio",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "περισσὸν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", used adverbially, literally “that which is over and above”; A. V[36], “more”; here, tropically = distinguished, unusually good = “quid magnum, eximium, insigne” (Pricaeus), so in ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Romans 3:1",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". In Plutarch, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "Romulus",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", xi., of one who excelled in casting horoscopes. Christ would awaken in disciples the ambition to excel. He does not wish them to be moral mediocrities, men of average morality, but to be morally superior, uncommon. This seems to come perilously near to the spirit of Pharisaism (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "cf.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Galatians 1:14",
        "children": []
      },
